@aruljeniston 
In this case we should implement following logic for read():
s = read();
if (s == -1 and errno != EINTR) go ahead.

We don't care about the data we read. We care about event, which poll() gave us.

> s = read();
> if (s == -1 and errno != EINTR) go ahead.

When read returns 0, what do we recommend?
Do we suggest to call read() again? or return back to poll()?
If the recommendation is to go back to poll(), there will be two events queued for one timer expiry and one of them is false alarm.  Don't we need to handle this false alarm?
Renuka has discussed the same in the second option. I have copied my understanding in pseudo-code below. Please correct me if I am missing anything.

while(1) 
{
  noof_events = poll()
  if (timerfd_event_qeued) {
    ret2 = read()
    if (ret2 == 0) {
      /* false alarm */
      goto poll:
    } else if (ret2 == 8) {
       /* timeout occured */
      /* take action */
    } else {
      /* error */
    }
  }
}

@jleveque The Linux v3.16 can return 0 as return value.
I don't think we need to work with partially returned value. How I see from the code it's always some error value, 0 or sizeof(uint64_t).
My comments above was about errno which is undefined when read returned 0.

> `APP_ACL_TABLE_NAME` shall be changed to `APP_ACL_TABLE_TABLE_NAME`
> the first table is for ACL_TABLE the second table is for TABLE_NAME
@stcheng  If we follow the "CFG_ACL_TABLE_NAME" name criteria APP_ACL_TABLE_NAME is suitable.

@qiluo-msft thanks for the comments!  
@zhenggen-xu found that this optimization does reduce the duplicate notifications for the same key. At very busy scenario,  the redis memory hog issue remains being seen though at slower rate than before.

Further debugging shows that even for unique notification per key, that is still too much for orchagent to handle.  In consumer_state_table_pops.lua,  we are performing batch spop for the key set.  The default batch value is 128,  orchagent has increased it to 8192.  That means if there are 8192 unique keys in the key set, only the first notification is taking real affect, the other 8191 notifications are consuming both memory and cpu power.   What makes it worse, in the case of route flapping, the keys are unique at different time span though they are repeating themselves,  unprocessed notification keeps accumulating.

@zhenggen-xu and I are trying further optimization,  there are some challenges with regards to the select() and redis publish processing.
